           <div style="float:right; margin:0 15px 5px 5px;">
           <%= link_to image_tag("weed4-thumb.jpg"), "assets/weed4.jpg", :rel => "lightbox", :alt => "", :title => "click to enlarge"%></div>
           
             <p><span style="font-weight:bold; color:#139901">Mango Haze</span></p>
             <p>Mango Haze is an overseas strain developed by Shantibaba of Mr Nice Seeds in Switzerland. It is described as "state of the art" in polyhybrid breeding technology. It is a very nice tasting strain with some CBD content and quite high THC. This is a good medical strain for those requiring something with a bit of kick while not being scary.  </p>
     
          <hr>


          <div style="float:left; margin:0 15px 5px 5px;">
           <%= link_to image_tag("weed5-thumb.jpg"), "assets/weed5.jpg", :rel => "lightbox", :alt => "", :title => "click to enlarge"%></div>
           
             <p><span style="font-weight:bold; color:#b701eb">Purple Mango</span></p>
           <p>This is the Haze used to make Purple Haze when it is crossed to Thai. It is not the same Purple Mango as the indica strain sold overseas. This is a sativa version. It's called Purple Mango because it smells like skunky mango and it turns purple. On it's own this is a heavy hitter that comes on fast and strong and can cause coughing fits. If you need high grade Medical Marijuana with a potency that will cut through the fogginess of some prescription meds then this strain is the one to go for. It can be a bit of a rollercoaster ride if you're not used to high potency marijuana so use with care.  </p>
     
          <hr>

          <div style="float:left; margin:0 15px 5px 5px;">
           <%= link_to image_tag("thai82-1-thumb.jpg"), "assets/thai82-1.jpg", :rel => "lightbox", :alt => "", :title => "click to enlarge"%></div>
           
             <p><span style="font-weight:bold; color:#139901">Thai82 Hybrid</span></p>
           <p>This is the strain used to make Purple Haze when it is crossed to Purple Mango. Thai82 is my signature strain that I've worked with for ten years. The original seeds came from a Thai Stick smuggled into Switzerland in 1982 where it was inbred for at least ten years. When I got it the strain was in a sorry state but I crossed it to a rare Highland Lao to restore vigour then used F2 crosses to get back to the Thai82 phenotypes.   </p>
           <p>The only downside to this strain is that being from equatorial Thailand it can take too long to start and finish flowering. For this reason a lot of my breeding work has been to bring the flowering forward and shorten the duration so it completes the flowering cycle in a temperate climate.
     
          <hr>

            <div style="float:left; margin:0 15px 5px 5px;">
           <%= link_to image_tag("thai82-2-thumb.jpg"), "assets/thai82-2.jpg", :rel => "lightbox", :alt => "", :title => "click to enlarge"%></div>
           
           <p>Thai82 hybrid is just a lovely plant all around. It is old school heirloom genetics that are no longer available in a pure form in Thailand (not this particular Thai strain). These genetics now only exist with collectors such as myself. The plant grows into a small tree with high pest and disease resistance. It is very variable at the F2 stage which is great for breeding with one in ten plants being outstanding. It has a lovely lemony mango scent and very mild taste. The effect is mellow and smooth with no paranoia making it an ideal all round medical strain.   </p>
     
